{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16612"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16612"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.02,0.23,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65975"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9303"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51424"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1474"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8765"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65975"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. His parent mentions noticing his right eye occasionally turning inward over the past few months. He was born at term with no complications and has no significant medical history. His immunisations are up to date and he takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is intermittent right esotropia. Picture chart visual acuity testing reveals 6/12 vision in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Red reflex is present bilaterally and equal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amblyopia","Congenital cataract","Accommodative spasm","Retinoblastoma","Optic nerve hypoplasia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of strabismic amblyopia, which develops due to suppression of visual input from the misaligned eye during critical periods of visual development. The combination of intermittent esotropia and reduced visual acuity in the affected eye is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmblyopia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of preventable vision loss in children, affecting 2-4% of the population. It occurs when there is a disruption to normal visual development, typically due to strabismus, significant refractive error differences between eyes (anisometropia), or visual deprivation. Early detection and treatment before age 7 years is crucial for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital cataract\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be noticed earlier in life and would be visible on examination as an opacity in the red reflex. The red reflex is normal in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinoblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with leukocoria (white pupillary reflex) and would be visible on red reflex testing. It can also present with strabismus, but the normal red reflex makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic nerve hypoplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a developmental abnormality that would be expected to cause more severe visual impairment and would be visible on fundoscopy. It typically does not cause strabismus as the primary feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccommodative spasm\u003C/strong\u003E can cause intermittent esotropia but would not typically cause unilateral reduced vision. It is also more common in older children and is often associated with headaches and blurred vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of amblyopia involves treating the underlying cause (glasses for refractive error if present) and patching or atropine penalisation of the good eye to force use of the amblyopic eye. Regular follow-up is essential to monitor progress and adjust treatment as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amblyopia should be suspected in children with strabismus, anisometropia, or structural abnormalities affecting vision.","Early detection and treatment of amblyopia before age 7 years offers the best visual outcomes.","Visual acuity testing methods must be age-appropriate, with picture charts for younger children and letter charts for older children."],"references":["Chen AM, Cotter SA. The Amblyopia Treatment Studies: Implications for Clinical Practice. Adv Ophthalmol Optom. 2016 Aug;1(1):287-305. doi: 10.1016/j.yaoo.2016.03.007. PMID: 28435934; PMCID: PMC5396957."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51424"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16612"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51424"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T12:18:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T12:18:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9303"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65975"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"at